<br>
This has always been my view on Christianity and the largest reason why I cannot accept it.<br>
If Jesus were really the incarnation of god, or knew he was the son of god, then well he knew he was not going to his end. Is that truly a noble of a sacrifice?<br>
<br>
Jesus bled and died for us? If you are christian you must concede then he truly did not die.  Being elevated to heaven cannot be see as something bad, now can it?  <br>
<br>
(I think I am right in this, tell me if i'm not) Jesus is viewed as a profit by Islaam.<br>
<br>
The view of him as a profit confers on him stronger status and a more heroic role.  He could then be viewed as someone who preached the will of god to his people despite being subject to rulers who would object to that.  In that scenario he truly was a man to be admired, as any other man trying to help his people through difficult times.  If he died because of what he believed in, that truly is noble and admirable.  One can still twist this using the religious idea of heaven, but usually someone who is doing things only to get into heaven often hasn't the courage to test if his deeds are sufficent.<br>
